From Henry Spencer Subject Re Public domain circuits in commercial applications In article David Prutchi writes Can circuits found in electronics magazines with no patent disclaimer be used legally as subcircuits of a commercial unit There are two issues here copyright and The magazine article's contents are copyrighted and may not be reproduced translated without the copyright holder's However this does not cover the ideas expressed only the form of Copying their circuit diagram or PC board pattern is copyright But it's unlikely that they could stretch copyright far enough to claim that the circuit design itself is So long as you draw your own diagrams and lay out your own boards copyright shouldn't be an Patents are The author does not have to give you any warning that the design is covered by patent although it would be sensible for him to do so In fact it's possible that he was infringing on someone else's patent without realizing Ignorance of the patented status is not a defence against infringement although it might reduce the damages a court would unless there was something seriously novel about the circuit almost certainly it is obvious to one skilled in the art and therefore Routine engineering is not patentable patents in theory cover only inventions ideas that are genuinely Caution I am not a Consulting a professional would be wise if significant amounts of money are at All work is one man's Henry Spencer U of Toronto Zoology Kipling utzoo henry